-- Japan, Korea, Taiwan, Malaysia, Singapore: Asian Bonds, Currency Previews
-- B y   P a t r i c i a   L u i
-- 2010-10-24T20:42:40Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-24/japan-korea-taiwan-malaysia-singapore-asian-bonds-currency-previews.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshito Sengoku will hold
media briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Ministry of Finance will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo
its report on the nation’s trade balance for September. Japan’s
trade surplus widened to 710 billion yen ($8.7 billion) in
September from a revised 86 billion yen surplus in August,
according to a Bloomberg News survey of economists.  The yield on the 0.8 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.89 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 81.32 per dollar at 5:35 a.m. in Tokyo.  Malaysia: The central bank will sell a total of 4 billion
ringgit ($1.3 billion) of 91- and 210-day notes. It will also
issue 1.5 billion ringgit of 126-day Islamic notes.  The yield on the 3.835 percent note due August 2015 was
3.30 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit was at
3.112 per dollar.  Singapore: The government will sell 3.7 billion Singapore
dollars ($2.8 billion) of 91-day Treasury bills.  The yield on the benchmark five-year note due July 2015 was
0.85 percent. The Singapore dollar traded at S$1.2956.  South Korea: The government will sell 600 billion won ($533
million) of 20-year bonds. The central bank will offer 1
trillion won of 91-day debt and 500 billion won of one-year
bonds.  The yield on the 4 percent note due September 2015 was 3.70
percent. The won was at 1,131.13 per dollar.  Taiwan: September industrial production increased by 14.95
percent from a year earlier after rising 23.4 percent in August,
according to a Bloomberg News survey. That would be the slowest
pace of growth since October, 2009.  The central bank will release September money supply data
today.  The yield on the 1.125 percent note due September 2020 was
1.23 percent, according to Gretai Securities Market, the
island’s biggest exchange for bonds. Taiwan’s dollar traded at
NT$30.910.  Singapore: The government will sell 3.7 billion Singapore
dollars ($2.8 billion) of 91-day Treasury bills.  The yield on the benchmark five-year note due July 2015 was
0.85 percent. The Singapore dollar traded at S$1.2956.  Financial markets in Thailand and the Philippines are
closed today.  To contact the reporter responsible for this story:
 Patricia Lui  at   plui4@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
